Project Name: Golden State Mutual Life Ins. Co. Records. Collection 1434
Name.creator: Golden State Mutual Life Insurance Co.--Employees
Title: Home Office Daily Operations
Description.note: A circa 1953 filmed tour of the Golden State Mutual Life Insurance Company West Adams home office shortly after it was built. Footage shows staffers at work in various departments, a detailed view of the office interiors and equipment and installation of a sign publicizing a new hospital plan. A number of key personnel appear such as Helen Batiste, Edgar J. Johnston, Ivan Houston, Verna Hickman, and co-founders George Beavers and Norman Houston. Also shown, a number of well-known African American entertainers and civil rights activists including Lena Horne, Joe Louis and Charlotta Bass.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this film is generously supported by funding from the National Film Preservation Foundation.

Project Name: Golden State Mutual Life Ins. Co. Records. Collection 1434
Name.creator: Golden State Mutual Life Insurance Co.--Employees
Title: GSM Company Picnic Movie 1958
Description.note: One of only two surviving examples in the collection of an annual outdoor event held for staffers and their families, celebrating the 1925 founding of the Golden State Mutual Life Insurance Company. The films are significant because they show local recreation sites frequented by African Americans during segregation. Over the years Golden State Mutual picnics were held at Val Verde (known as the “Black Palm Springs”), Santa Monica Beach between Bay and Bicknel streets (colloquially referred to as “The Ink Spot” or “Ink Well Beach”), Cabrillo Beach and Lake Elsinore.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this film is generously supported by funding from the National Film Preservation Foundation.

Description.note: One of only two surviving examples in the collection of an annual outdoor event held for staffers and their families, celebrating the 1925 founding of the Golden State Mutual Life Insurance Company. The films are significant because they show local recreation sites frequented by African Americans during segregation. Over the years Golden State Mutual picnics were held at Val Verde (known as the “Black Palm Springs”), Santa Monica Beach between Bay and Bicknel streets (colloquially referred to as “The Ink Spot” or “Ink Well Beach”), Cabrillo Beach and Lake Elsinore. This footage was shot at Val Verde.

Project Name: Golden State Mutual Life Ins. Co. Records. Collection 1434
Name.creator: Golden State Mutual Life Insurance Co.--Employees
Title: Home Office construction, office opening in 1949
Description.note: Shows ground-breaking and opening ceremonies of the Golden State Mutual Life Insurance Company's West Adams Los Angeles home office. Co-founder Norman Houston and colleague looking at blueprints. Installation of murals  painted by Charles Alston and  Hale Woodruff. Grand opening includes ribbon cutting ceremony and unveiling of the mural and the bust of founder William Nickerson, Jr. Also shown, the placement of the time capsule and cornerstone. Documentation on film leader indicates "Original to be used for reprint only."
Description.fundingNote: Access to this film is generously supported by funding from the National Film Preservation Foundation.
